Rabies, raccoons - USA (Connecticut) 981126012544
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 16:19:33 -0500
From: Dardick, Kenneth <kdardick@wcmh.org>

With all due respect to Dr. Cumming's observations ("...Rabies is a new
thing up this way as of late...") - the rabies epizootic has been
well-described here in Connecticut and particularly in Northeastern
Connecticut since at least March 1991 (see MMWR 4/22/94, V43 No 15). It was
the re-introduction of wild raccoon rabies into Connecticut which prompted
the legislature to pass the law mandating rabies vaccination for all cats
(PA 91-46, 1991).
The raccoon die-off described from 3 years ago, was actually the second
wave of deaths among raccoons in this area as rabies-naive animals who were
not living in 1991-1993 matured and were infected and died. We can expect
similar waves every 3-5 years. It is critical from a public health
perspective to continue to teach rabies-awareness in our schools - this is
as important for the curriculum as sex education and proper nutrition!
Children and adults must be taught the critical importance of avoiding
contact with all wild animals and domestic animals which are not known to
be vaccinated. The "Disney syndrome" of petting cute wild critters must be
shown to be reckless and dangerous behavior.
--
Kenneth R. Dardick, MD FACP DTM&H
Connecticut Travel Medicine, Storrs,
CT and Eastern Highlands Health District (Mansfield/Coventry/Bolton)
e-mail: kdardick@wcmh.org
[An additional reason for not petting wild animals is that it is very
stressful for them. Unless hand-reared they do not enjoy the experience and
are severely threatened by it. Adult animals will do a lot of damage to
naive humans if the latter insist on coming too close. - Mod.MHJ
