[2
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 09:47:02 -0500
From: Angela M. Lee, Special Correspondent to ProMED-mail <finchley@flash.net>

An account of another highly inadvisable action (although kindly meant)
taken by some maintenance workers at a large company in Maryland a few
years ago ......
At a large chemical research company here, located on some several-acre
grassy campus surrounded by woods, some maintenance workers who
'brown-bagged' lunch, took to feeding leftover morsels to a couple of
raccoons. They were apparently enchanted by the fact that the raccoons
walked right up to them in broad daylight and would feed from the workers'
hands. They did not stop to think (as was later confirmed) that the
raccoons were acting highly out of the norm and were, indeed, rabid.
--
Angela Lee
e-mail: finchley@flash.net
[We had a similar occasion here in east Baton Rouge two summers ago when a
lonely old lady was regularly feeding a bunch of feral cats and
free-loading raccoons. One of the latter was diagnosed with rabies. But
read on ... - Mod.MHJ
