[3
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 19:02:16 EST
From: PJ Deitschel <Deitschel@aol.com>

A comment is needed regarding the statement by Mod.MHJ "Any wild raccoon in
a public place in daylight is virtually pathognomonic for a very suspect
rabies case".
On Sanibel Island in Florida our raccoons are considered "tidal". Their
normal behavior is to forage for food during low tide whether that be
during the day or night. At 'Care and Rehabilitation For Wildlife' we spend
many hours each week reassuring our island visitors from northern states
that the raccoons passing through their yards during the day are not rabid
but simply hungry.
--
PJ Deitschel
C.R.O.W. Staff Veterinarian
e-mail: crowclinic@aol.com
